# Risk Manager (Sales & Trading)

## Overview
Risk managers in Sales & Trading divisions provide independent oversight of trading activities, measuring and monitoring market, credit, and operational risk to ensure banks operate within approved risk limits and regulatory requirements.

## Core Responsibilities
- Calculate Value-at-Risk (VaR), stress testing, scenario analysis, and sensitivity metrics (Greeks) for trading portfolios on a daily basis
- Track trading positions against approved VaR, position, loss, and concentration limits, investigating and documenting any breaches that occur
- Produce daily, weekly, and monthly risk reports for traders, senior management, and board risk committees detailing exposures and limit utilization
- Review and challenge pricing models, risk models, and trading algorithms developed by quantitative analysts to ensure they are fit for purpose
- Ensure risk management practices meet APRA prudential standards, Basel III capital requirements, and the FRTB regulatory framework
- Design and run stress scenarios to assess portfolio resilience under extreme market conditions and validate models through backtesting exercises

## Key Skills Required

### Technical Skills
- Strong quantitative skills in statistics, probability, calculus, and linear algebra
- Programming proficiency in Python (essential), R (useful), and VBA (helpful)
- Advanced Excel skills including pivot tables, complex formulas, and data analysis
- Deep understanding of financial instruments: bonds, derivatives, FX, and equities
- Knowledge of risk metrics including VaR, Greeks, stress testing, PV01, and DV01
- Familiarity with risk systems such as Murex, Summit, Calypso, and Bloomberg MARS
- Comprehensive understanding of Basel III and FRTB capital frameworks

### Interpersonal Skills
- Exceptional attention to detail and accuracy in all risk calculations
- Clear communication of complex technical concepts to non-specialist audiences
- Professional skepticism with ability to challenge traders appropriately
- Strong time management under daily deadline pressure (morning reports due by 8am)
- Effective stakeholder management and ability to influence without direct authority

### Regulatory Knowledge
- Expert knowledge of APRA prudential standards (APS 115, 116, 117, 180)
- Understanding of Basel III market risk framework and FRTB implementation
- Awareness of three lines of defense model and risk governance principles

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (60-70%)
Risk calculations using VaR models, data extraction from trading systems, stress testing scenarios, model backtesting, regulatory capital calculations, and investigating unusual P&L movements or risk metric changes.

### Meetings & Stakeholder Management (15-25%)
Daily risk meetings with trading desks, weekly risk committee presentations, monthly management reporting sessions, engaging with senior traders on positions and limits, and presenting to board risk committees.

### Systems & Operations (10-15%)
Maintaining risk databases, reconciling position data with middle office, testing and implementing system upgrades, quality control checks, and documenting methodologies and data sources for audit purposes.

### Model Governance & Validation (10-15%)
Reviewing quant model documentation, backtesting VaR models against actual outcomes, testing pricing models against market quotes, supporting independent validation teams, and maintaining validation schedules.

### Strategic Risk Projects (5-10%)
Designing new stress scenarios (including climate risk), enhancing limit frameworks for new products, researching emerging risk methodologies, and supporting regulatory examinations and audit requests.

## Workplace Culture
Risk teams sit near trading floors but maintain independence, balancing business partnership with independent oversight. Fast-paced environment with early starts (6:30am) for daily reporting, combining quantitative depth with commercial awareness.

## Career Path
- Entry: Graduate/Junior Risk Analyst (AU$70K-100K + AU$10K-25K bonus)
- Progression: Risk Analyst → Senior Risk Analyst → Market Risk Manager → Head of Market Risk → Chief Risk Officer

